Why learn a computer programming language?

Do you work on a computer?

If so, it's likely you could benefit in some way by learning a programming language.

Using a computer without programming skills is like:

…advocating for water quality without understanding the science: you may be able to change the behavior of a few people with your persuasion alone, but you will be much more effective if you can properly communicate the implications of poor water quality, its causes, and the opportunities for restoration.

Using a computer without programming skills is like:

…making pesto with a knife instead of a food processor: most of the time you're cutting each pine nut one at a time, and occasionally you can get a few all at once. With a food processor, it may take longer to set up, but once it's ready you can make a year's worth of pesto in 10 minutes and the result will be much more consistent.

Using a computer without programming skills is like:

…making cake with a wheat seed and a baby chicken: rather than beginning from raw materials every time, it would be more effective to first raise many egg-producing chickens, replicate your wheat seed into a field of seed-yielding plants, and build a tool for processing seeds into flour.

What is so special about the R language?

R will soon be the language preferred by most scientists. Measured by Google Scholar hits, R recently surpassed SAS, and will soon surpass SPSS which has been trending precipitously downward for the last 7 years.

What is so special about the R language?

R is extremely extensible. It was originally designed to be used solely for data analysis and graphics. However, the scope of its use has increased dramatically to include automation, interactivity with other languages, application and web development, GIS, database management, and much more. The key is the involvement of a large (and growing) user base that contributes to the project.

What is so special about the R language?

R is free

R can do all sorts of amazing things

Tour of RStudio

Tour of RStudio

R comes in lots of different flavors, but the way that we will be using R for this class is through a software package called RStudio. RStudio packages many of the things you need to be a productive programmer all in place.

RStudio can help beginner programmers learn quickly, but it also has enough functionality to satisfy the advanced programmer as well.

To start, let's get a feel for the RStudio interface.

Tour of RStudio

First, open RStudio software by clicking on the Windows Start button and typing "rstudio":

Tour of RStudio

how to set up your desktop for the class

Tour of RStudio

There are a number of windows in R, but we are going to start by using only one, the R console:

Tour of RStudio

The R console allows you to type in R code interactively and print the result.

RStudio has many fancy functions, of which we will discuss in more detail as we go along, but basic R software (as opposed to RStudio) is essentially just the console, so you can mentally equate the R program with the mental image of the R console.

It's a commmand prompt (>, the place where you type in code), plain and simple.

Tour of RStudio

Let's try writing our first line of code. One of the most basic elements of any computer programming language is simple math. Try typing in 2+2 at the command prompt, and hit enter:

2+2
## [1] 4

Tour of RStudio

Notice that the R console returns the result of that mathematical statement.

There is a little bracketed [1] next to the result–all that means is that first item is listed directly to the right–we will come back to this later, but for now you can ignore it.

Exercise

Let's take 5 minutes to try out different mathematical statements. Try using different mathematical operators such as addition/subtraction (+, -), multiplication/division ( *, /), and exponents (^), and parentheses.

Basic R Syntax

[sin-taks]

the rules/form of a computer programming language (e.g., characters, symbols, whitespace)

Variables

When we type in a mathematical statement in the R console and press enter, it returns the results as a message printed on the screen.

As an alternative to having the result returned as a message, we can also save the result to be used later. We do this by assigning the result to a variable.

Variables

To tell R to assign a value to a variable, We will use the equals sign (=):

my_1st_variable = 5

Variables

We can name the variable anything we want. Here I named it my_1st_variable, but I could just as well have named it theodore_roosevelt.

The only rule with naming variables is that it cannot contain a space, special characters, or start with a number.

Variables

Think of a variable as a container that you can put anything into–you can also take things out or modify the contents, which is why they are called "variables".

Once the contents are stored, we can re-use them as though they have the same value as the contents themselves:

my_1st_variable + 5
## [1] 10

Variables

As you create more and more variables, RStudio has a helpful tool for you to keep track of them. There is a tab called "Environment" in the upper-right panel that lists all of your variables for you.

Variables

In the same way we write mathematical equations, variables take on the value of the right-hand side of the equation. For example:

x = 2 + 2
x + 2
## [1] 6

So what is the value of x?

Variables

Note: we can use either an equals sign (=) or an arrow (<-)–which is just the less-than sign followed by a hyphen–to assign a variable. If you want to bring the purist trolls out of the woodwork, ask Google which one you should use. If you want to keep it simple, just pick one and stick with it. In other words, it really doesn't matter which one you use, just be aware of both when reading other people's code

Exercise

Take 2-3 minutes to try out variable assignment using mathematical operators. Try re-using variables in mathematical statements.

Scripts

You've probably begun to notice that it is tedious to write every statement of code, line-by-line, one-at-a-time, at the command prompt in the R console. Fortunately, you will not have to do this any longer. Enter the script.

A script contains many lines of code that can be executed simultaneously. It is a file stored on your hard drive, much like a .docx or .xlsx file, except it has a .r extension instead.

Scripts

RStudio has a feature that makes it very easy to create a script. In the file menu, click new file, and then click R script. A new blank pane should appear:

Scripts

We are going to save this file on our hard drive, but first, a little house cleaning. We've set up an RStudio project for you, which is simply a way of containing many useful elements relating to a project in one place. In the file menu, click Open Project, navigate to the place you stored the course pack, and select the file called "r_workshop.Rproj". Doing so will set up our R session to work out of our course pack folder.

Scripts

You can verify this by clicking the Files tab in the lower-right pane:

A window like the one above should appear with files associated with our class.

Scripts

Now, let's save our R script.

First, type in a couple lines of code:

x = 2 + 2
x + 2

Click the save button () on our R script pane:

Scripts

Notice that RStudio recognizes certain characters and changes their colors. Although you are ultimately writing to a simple text file, because its file extension is ".r", RStudio recognizes that it contains R code, and then helps you visualize it through color.

Scripts

One of the most useful features of the RStudio IDE is the ability to run the code in your scripts in your console. With your cursor on the same line as x = 2 + 2, press Ctrl+Enter.

Scripts

Your scripts can also contain comments to help you and others understand your code. To add a comment, start with the hash symbol (#). Anything after # will not be executed until you start a new line.

# This line is not executed
x = 2 + 2 # but this one is

As you are working through the course material, it may be helpful for you to write notes as comments.

Exercise

Create a brand new script, write a few lines of code using variables and mathematical statements, and start getting in the habit of writing notes to yourself as #comments.

Functions

One way to add 2 + 2:

2+2
## [1] 4

Simple, but could get cumbersome with long sequences of numbers

Another way to add 2 + 2:

sum(2,2)
## [1] 4

More flexible and concise method

Functions

Sum is a function. An R function does something. It is an action statement. Functions are the verbs of computer programming.

The way we use functions in R is by typing their name followed by parentheses (without a space in between). The contents of the parentheses are called the arguments. Arguments are how we tell the function what to do. If "jump" were a function, the argument would by "how high?".

The arguments of the sum function are the values we want to add together. We separate arguments of a function with commas.

Functions

So how do we know what arguments to use for each function? We can use R help for that. There are two ways to access help for R functions. The first is to use the RStudios help tab in the lower-right pane:

Functions

Or, we can simply type a question mark followed by the function name in our console:

?sum

Functions

A core function in R that you will become very familiar with is the c() function. The c() function allows you to create a vector of values. A vector is a sequence of values:

y = c(3,5,7)
print(y)
## [1] 3 5 7

Here, the print() function prints y in the console.

Functions

In R, you can do math across vectors:

z = y * 2
print(z)
## [1]  6 10 14

Functions

This may not seem like much, but one of the most powerful aspects of R, and what sets it apart from many other computer programming languages is its ability to do math across sequences of numbers–it is what we refer to as an "array-based language".

Exercise

Let's take 20 minutes to explore mathematical operators, variables, and functions. Try using vectors with other functions, such as the mean() and stdev() (standard deviation) functions.

5-MINUTE BREAK

Data.frames

If you are accustomed to using Excel or Access, the data.frame object in R should be very intuitive for you. A data.frame is just a table of data.

In a data.frame, each column has a name and number that identify the data in it, and the data within a column is all the same type.

Before we use data.frames in R, let's look at the table that we'd like to use. Open the Vilas_TP_CHL_data.csv file in Excel (in the /data folder) and familiarize yourself with the data.

Data.frames

Now we want to read that data into R. To do this, we will use the read.csv function. Remember, you can use the help menu to get details on how to use a function.

?read.csv

For this function, the key argument is a "text string" representing the path to the file you're inputting.

All of the other arguments (header, sep, nrows, skip, etc.) have default values and are thus not required to be entered by the user. Default values are shown in the Usage section with an = sign: read.csv(file,header=TRUE).

Data.frames

Let's use what we've learned about read.csv to load in the data.frame

d = read.csv("data/Vilas_TP_CHL_data.csv")

Notice how we give the file name and its location within the data folder? Because we are using an RStudio project, our working directory is the folder associated with the project - in this case, it is the r_workshop folder. So, our file path starting with "data/" tells R to look for a folder called data within r_workshop

Data.frames

Once we have the data.frame read into R and saved as an object, we'll want to view it, check that the data were read in correctly, check column names, check numbers of rows and columns, etc. Since you don't always have a spreadsheet of the data in front of you, it's useful to become familiar with interpreting these attributes of your data. We can explore our data.frame in a few ways.

First, let's introduce a few useful functions. str (meaning "structure") is one you should become fluent in. For a data.frame, it only requires one argument: the name of your data.frame. Let's see the structure of our data.frame:

str(d)

Data.frames

str(d)
## 'data.frame':    4213 obs. of  5 variables:
##  $ ID  : int  643401 643137 643137 643401 643402 643407 643080 643401 643137 643249 ...
##  $ NAME: Factor w/ 200 levels "Afterglow Lake - Deep Hole",..: 7 136 136 7 71 45 110 7 136 140 ...
##  $ DATE: Factor w/ 1541 levels "1993-05-12","1993-05-17",..: 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 8 8 ...
##  $ CHL : num  4.01 11.6 9.14 3.54 2.36 2.95 3.21 3.06 12.2 7.88 ...
##  $ TP  : num  11 39 23 9 20 9 13 10 30 16 ...

There are a few useful outputs: the number of observations (rows) and variables (columns), the name of each column, whether each column is numeric, integer, etc. (more on data.types next), and the first several entries of each column.

Data.frames

Sometimes, it's easier to just look at the data.frame in table form though. To do that, we can just run print(d) or d for short. This will print the data.frame in the console, but gets messy if you have more than a few rows or columns.

One way to get around that is to use head or tail which only show you the top or bottom of your data.frame, but can still be messy if we have many columns.

head(d)
##       ID                         NAME       DATE   CHL TP
## 1 643401       Anvil Lake - Deep Hole 1993-05-12  4.01 11
## 2 643137 Muskellunge Lake - Deep Hole 1993-05-17 11.60 39
## 3 643137 Muskellunge Lake - Deep Hole 1993-06-15  9.14 23
## 4 643401       Anvil Lake - Deep Hole 1993-06-21  3.54  9
## 5 643402      Harris Lake - Deep Hole 1993-06-28  2.36 20
## 6 643407        Crab Lake - Deep Hole 1993-06-29  2.95  9

Data.frames

Finally, RStudio has another nice feature that lets us view our data.frame a little more like a spreadsheet - just double-click on the name of your data.frame in the Environment window or use View(df).

Data.frames

If we just want to see the names of the variables, we can use names or colnames.

colnames(d)
## [1] "ID"   "NAME" "DATE" "CHL"  "TP"

Finally, we may want some idea of how big our data.frame is. To get the number of rows, use nrow. For the number of columns, use ncol.

nrow(d)
## [1] 4213

Data.frames

What if we just want to look at a particular column? To access a particular column from a data.frame, we can use $ in conjunction with the column name. Say we just want to look at the lake names in our dataset. We know that column is called "NAME". To access it, we use:

d$NAME

Data.frames

Organization

The way a data.frame is set up dictates how they can be used in analyses. The two general types of setups for tabular data are wide (or unstacked) and long (or stacked or tall). Generally, these are both more analysis-friendly than using multiple excel worksheets (one tab per lake, for instance).

Wide data

Wide data.frames contain a separate column for each variable, so there is one row for each subject.

Long data

In long data, each subject can have multiple rows - one for each separate sampling event, for instance.

Data.frames

Organization

Take a look at d. What format is it?

Data.frames

Organization

Take a look at d. What format is it?

Long data structures are generally more suitable for analyses than *wide data, because it is easier to reference a particular column (TP) than a set of columns (2009_TP, 2010_TP…).

However, one downside of long data is that it is a little bit more difficult to access some summary types of information, like the number of stations in the dataset, or the sample size for each.

These are things we could do in an Excel pivot table. How can we do the same sorts of things in R?

Data.frames

Using long data.frames

One useful function is unique, which pulls out unique values. We can use it in conjunction with length (which counts the number of items in a vector) to get the number of stations, for instance.

length(unique(d$ID))
## [1] 202

Data.frames

Using long data.frames

A little more advanced is the table function, which runs a cross-tabulation to count the number of observations (rows) for each factor. We can use this to get a table of sample sizes, assuming each row = 1 sample

table(d$ID)

Data.frames

Using long data.frames

Finally, the aggregate function allows you to pass other functions to subsets of the data.frame. For instance, we can calculate the mean TP for each station ID. You can think of the following code as "Pass the mean function to each set of TP values, where sets are defined by unique IDs"

aggregate(d$TP,by=list(d$ID),mean)

Use length and unique to figure out how many unique days sampling occurred on.

Data Types

Let's say you are working in Excel, and you want to create a column that contains quantities of money associated with different people.

Data Types

Then, let's say you want to divide those quantities by two:

Data Types

If we apply that same function to all cells in that column, we get an error when Excel tries to calculate half of the value "unknown"

This is because Excel does not recognize the "unknown" value as something divisible. The "unknown" value is a different data type. The division operator in Excel only recognizes numeric data types and therefore throws in error, and R will do the same with mismatches in data types.

Data Types

There are many data types in R, but in this section, we'll introduce 6 important types: numeric, integer, character, logical, factor, and date.

Data Types

Numbers

The two data types that represent numbers are "numeric" and "integer". A numeric data type is a quantity with a decimal point (sometimes referred to as "float" or "double" in other programming languages), and an integer is a quantity without a decimal point, simple as that! You can use the class function to query the data type of a value:

class(1.5)
class(1)
## [1] "numeric"
## [1] "numeric"

Data Types

Numbers

Notice that value of 1 is defined as a numeric data type. If you want to be explicit about defining an integer, you must use a coercion function. Each data type has a coercion function–the name of the function is just the data type preceded by as., such as as.numeric or as.integer.

class(as.integer(1))
## [1] "integer"

Data Types

Characters

"Characters" (often referred to as "strings" in other programming languages) can include alphabet letters, digits, and special symbols, but are all treated as text. Characters can be defined by wrapping them in quotes:

class("This is a character data type")
class("Numbers (1) and symbols ($) can be included in characters")
class("1")
## [1] "character"
## [1] "character"
## [1] "character"

Data Types

Characters

You can also coerce a value to a character using its coercion function:

char_var = as.character(1.52342)
print(char_var)
## [1] "1.52342"
class(char_var)
## [1] "character"

Data Types

Characters

When dealing with characters, likely the most common function that you will use is the paste function. The paste function concatenates character strings together:

paste("a", "b", "c")
## [1] "a b c"

Data Types

Characters

Notice that the paste function separates each string with a space by default. To change the separation character, use the sep argument:

paste("a", "b", "c", sep=",")
## [1] "a,b,c"
paste("a", "b", "c", sep="")
## [1] "abc"

Data Types

Logical

"Logical" is the simplest data type because it can take only two values, TRUE and FALSE:

class(TRUE)
## [1] "logical"

Data Types

Logical

The values TRUE and FALSE are only considered logical data type if written in these ways:

# All caps
class(TRUE)
class(FALSE)
# Capital T or F
class(T)
class(F)
# 0 or 1
class(as.logical(0))
class(as.logical(1))

Data Types

Factors

Factors are a data type that describes categories. They are similar to character data types because they will appear the same when you print them, but they are different in how the data is stored in memory. It only makes sense to talk about factors when there is more than one, so let's explore a factor column in a data.frame.

Data Types

Factors

Remember that the str function can help us explore a data.frame:

str(d)
## 'data.frame':    4213 obs. of  5 variables:
##  $ ID  : int  643401 643137 643137 643401 643402 643407 643080 643401 643137 643249 ...
##  $ NAME: Factor w/ 200 levels "Afterglow Lake - Deep Hole",..: 7 136 136 7 71 45 110 7 136 140 ...
##  $ DATE: Factor w/ 1541 levels "1993-05-12","1993-05-17",..: 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 8 8 ...
##  $ CHL : num  4.01 11.6 9.14 3.54 2.36 2.95 3.21 3.06 12.2 7.88 ...
##  $ TP  : num  11 39 23 9 20 9 13 10 30 16 ...

Data Types

Factors

Notice that the NAME column has 200 levels

str(d$NAME)
##  Factor w/ 200 levels "Afterglow Lake - Deep Hole",..: 7 136 136 7 71 45 110 7 136 140 ...

This means there are 200 unique values.

Data Types

Factors

In a factor column, R assigns an integer to each unique value, or level:

str(d$NAME)
##  Factor w/ 200 levels "Afterglow Lake - Deep Hole",..: 7 136 136 7 71 45 110 7 136 140 ...

Data Types

Factors

This storage strategy serves two purposes:

  1. It consumes less memory. In most cases, character strings require more memory than integers.
  2. It allows us to use character representations as a variable in a statistical model without using a character-to-integer lookup table.

Data Types

Dates

str(d$DATE)
##  Factor w/ 1541 levels "1993-05-12","1993-05-17",..: 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 8 8 ...

Note that the DATE column is formatted as chr. It needs to be coerced to a Date data type to make plots with time as an axis, to subset based on date ranges, etc.

d$DATE = as.Date(d$DATE)

NA, a special R value

There is a special value in R to denote "missing data". The value is NA. A couple things to know about NA values:

  1. Doing math on vectors with any NA values will result in NA unless the na.rm=TRUE argument is specified (e.g., sum(x, na.rm=TRUE))
  2. is.na is a special function for finding NA values that will return TRUE for missing values and FALSE for anything else
  3. Some R functions will smartly handle NA values and/or tell you how they've been handled, but others functions will handle them implicitly without telling you what they did. Use the help menu!

Exercise

Take 5 minutes to test different functionality on different data types to see how R behaves (for example, try dividing an integer or multiplying by a character). Try integrating NA values into your expressions to test behavior.

5-MINUTE BREAK

Slicing/Subsetting/Filtering

Our data is now stored in memory as a variable in R. However, we will likely need to do some further manipulation of our data.frame. A very common task is to slice/subset/filter (words that all mean the same thing) the data, which means that we will pull certain rows and/or columns from the full data.frame.

Slicing/Subsetting/Filtering

The subset function selects certain rows from a data.frame based on whether a condition is met. It is very similar to using the "Filter" button in Excel:

Slicing/Subsetting/Filtering

There are two primary ways to slice/subset/filter:

  1. By index
  2. By condition

Let's try indexing first…

Slicing/Subsetting/Filtering

Indexing

Indexing defines the row or column number (i.e. the "index") to be selected. The syntax is square brackets with the indices of rows and columns contained in them, with row and column indices seperated by a comma:

d[1,2]
## [1] Anvil Lake - Deep Hole
## 200 Levels: Afterglow Lake - Deep Hole ... Yellow Birch Lake at Max Depth

This statement selects the item in the 1st row and 2nd column

Slicing/Subsetting/Filtering

Indexing

To select all rows or columns, simply leave the bracketed position blank. This statement will select all columns in the first row

d[1,]
##       ID                   NAME       DATE  CHL TP
## 1 643401 Anvil Lake - Deep Hole 1993-05-12 4.01 11

Slicing/Subsetting/Filtering

Indexing

To select a range of rows or columns, use the colon symbol. This statement will select the first five rows and first two columns:

d[1:5,1:2]
##       ID                         NAME
## 1 643401       Anvil Lake - Deep Hole
## 2 643137 Muskellunge Lake - Deep Hole
## 3 643137 Muskellunge Lake - Deep Hole
## 4 643401       Anvil Lake - Deep Hole
## 5 643402      Harris Lake - Deep Hole

Exercise (5 minutes)

Select the 10th through 50th rows of the NAME and DATE columns. Extra credit: try selecting a single column by name instead of by index. Try selecting multiple columns by name.

Slicing/Subsetting/Filtering

Condition

We can also subset using conditional statements. First, what is a conditional statement?

A conditional statement is a comparison that evaluates to either true or false.

We compare things using logical operators.

Slicing/Subsetting/Filtering

Condition

Logical Operator Definition
< Less than
<= Less than or equal to
> greater than
>= greater than or equal to
== exactly equal to
!= not equal to
| logical "or"
& logical "and"

Slicing/Subsetting/Filtering

Condition

A silly axiomatic comparison:

a = 2
print(a == 2)
## [1] TRUE

Slicing/Subsetting/Filtering

Condition

Multiple comparisons:

print(d$TP < 30)

Slicing/Subsetting/Filtering

Condition

To slice/subset/filter using conditions instead of indexes, all you have to do is replace the index value in the square brackets with a conditional statement. R will return the rows/columns where the conditional statement evaluates to true.

This statement will select all columns, but only the rows where TP is greater than 40:

d_sub = d[d$TP > 40,]

Exercise (5 minutes)

Select all rows of d where TP has values between 10 and 40. Extra credit: Select all samples taken since 2007 that have TP values between 10 and 40.

Scatterplots

  • A HUGE benefit of R is its ability to produce customizable, complex, and downright pretty visualizations of data. A drawback of a 2-day workshop is that we can't quite teach you all of that.

  • We can teach you the basics, which act as building blocks toward higher-level graphics.

Scatterplots

We'll come back to making figures tomorrow, but by this point in the workshop, you've earned the right to see what the data look like outside of a data.frame. The key building block in making graphics is the plot function. This is a highly versatile function - it can take lots of different data and object types as inputs. The default usage is to just give it x and y coordinates in the form plot(x,y), and it will output a scatterplot. In RStudio, this will show up in its own panel. The x and y arguments can be single values, vectors of values, or columns from a data.frame.

plot(d$TP,d$CHL)

Scatterplots

plot(d$TP,d$CHL)

Exercise (5 min)

Use your data.frame to play around with making simple scatterplots. Try to use subsetting to remake the plot for different lakes.

Try using some of the different plot arguments, if you have time. We'll come back to those tomorrow.

For loops

Much of our work at DNR involves running the same general set of analytical steps on many units (e.g., monitoring stations, water bodies, permits, etc.). This can get a bit tedious, and is prone to error. Do you ever find yourself wondering, "If only I could program my computer to run these steps on all my sites, and then spend my time evaluating the results…"?

With for loops in R, you can!

A for loop automates a process by applying the same step(s) to one or more items. Related terms include "batch process" and "iterate".

Control-flow constructs

  • if(cond) expr
  • if(cond) cons.expr else alt.expr
  • for(var in seq) expr
  • while(cond) expr
  • repeat expr
  • break
  • next

if statements

if(cond) expr

  • One of the key elements in complex programming
  • Allows you to execute sections of code if one or more conditions are met
if((2+2)==4) { # expr enclosed with {}
  print("Math is real!")
}
## [1] "Math is real!"

For loops

for(var in seq) expr

Let's start simple:

s = c(1:5) # create seq
for(i in s) { # i for index
  print(i)
}
## [1] 1
## [1] 2
## [1] 3
## [1] 4
## [1] 5

What it does:

i=1
print(i)
i=2
print(i)
i=3
print(i)
i=4
print(i)
i=5
print(i)

For loops

for(var in seq) expr

Now let's make print conditional on i not being 3:

for(i in s) {
  if(i!=3) { # != means not equal
    print(i)
  }
}
## [1] 1
## [1] 2
## [1] 4
## [1] 5

For loops: Best practices

for(var in seq) expr

  • Enclose expr in {}
  • Test the loop on a short seq
  • Factor out common operations rather than repeating them
  • Vectorize slow for loops
  • Include error handling code (e.g., break, next)
  • Nested loops
    • Enclose each level in {}, and indent
    • Use a new var for each level

Exercise

Write a for loop that prints the square roots of the numbers 4, 9, and 16.

Challenge: Write a for loop that prints the number of samples at each station in the Vilas dataset (d) if the number is >=6.

One solution to the challenge exercise

stations = unique(d$ID) # create vector of unique station IDs
for(s in stations) { 
  n = nrow(d[d$ID==s,]) # number of samples at station s
  if(n>=6) print(paste("Station",s,"has",n,"samples"))
}

For loops

Email from Dan Helsel to Matt Diebel regarding Dead Pike Lake clarity trends:

I saw Dr. Carpenter’s comment about “similar to trends I have seen in a lot of Northern Wisconsin lakes. Transparency increases after the 2006 drought, and decreases back toward historical values after 2012 or 2013.” So I started messing with the vilas and iron county secchi disk readings to see if I could “verify” his statement. …I’m wondering if there’s an easy way to select some lakes in those counties to see if we have similar trends. My adolescent ability to function within excel got me to the point of trying to graph seasonal trends on 50+ lakes (see sheet #2) – Aaaargh. Any suggestions or ideas?

For loops

Prepare data

data = read.csv("data/Vilas_County_Secchi_1995-2017.csv", as.is=TRUE)
data$Date = as.Date(data$Date, format="%m/%d/%Y")
data$Year = as.numeric(format(data$Date, "%Y"))
stations = aggregate(data$Date, 
  by=list(data$StationID,data$StationName), 
  FUN=length)
colnames(stations) = c("ID","NAME","COUNT")
stations = stations[stations$COUNT>=6,]
stations = stations[order(stations$NAME),]
xlims = c(min(data$Date), max(data$Date))
xgrid = as.Date(paste(c(399:403*5),"-01-01",sep=""))

For loops

Put all plots into a single pdf

pdf("plots/Vilas_County_Secchi_1995-2017_plots.pdf", 
  width=8.5, height=11)
par(mfrow=c(3,2), oma=c(2,2,2,2))
for (s in 1:nrow(stations)) {
  sdata = data[data$StationID==stations$ID[s],]
  if(length(unique(sdata$Year))<10) {next}
  plot(Secchi~Date, sdata, type="n", 
    xlab="", ylab="Secchi Depth (ft)", 
    ylim=c(max(sdata$Secchi),0), xlim=xlims,
    main=paste(stations$ID[s]," - ",stations$NAME[s], sep=""), 
    cex.main=0.9)
  abline(h=c(0:10*5), v=xgrid, col="lightgray")
  points(Secchi~Date, sdata)
  box()
}
dev.off()

End of Day 1…BUT, just one more slide

A note about closing RStudio

Every time you close RStudio, it will ask you if you want to save an RData file. An RData file saves all your variables (in memory) to a file (hard drive). This can be useful if you want to pick up where you left off at another time with all your variables read back into memory. Please save the RData file to your thumb drive.

Generally, it is MOST important to save your script. That is your main working document, and takes up very little storage space. You can always rerun the script the next time you work on a project.

Logistics

Picking up where we left off

Today, we'll start with a fresh script, and we'll try to keep it nicely organized. Start with this at the top of your script.

###### READ IN MY DATA #######
model = read.csv("data/TP_CHL_models.csv")
d = read.csv("data/Vilas_TP_CHL_data.csv")
d$DATE = as.Date(d$DATE)
#####

In RStudio, lots of #####s (4 or more) wrapped around a title can be used to denote sections. You should be able to click the little down arrow next to the first line to collapse the whole section.

More detailed plotting

Yesterday, we showed you how to make simple scatterplots. But, there are numerous other types of plots you can make, infinite ways to customize them, and some techniques for creating publication or web-quality figures. Today, we'll introduce you to a bit of all of the above.

Other plot types

The basic plot command is versatile and can take various types of input arguments, but there are other functions. For instance, if you want to make a boxplot, then the boxplot command might suit you.

boxplot(d$TP,log="y")

Other plot types

Or using formula notation…

#subset lakes to those w/ "Dead Pike" in name:
deadpike = d[grepl("Dead Pike",d$NAME),] 
deadpike$NAME = factor(deadpike$NAME) #reset factors
boxplot(deadpike$TP~deadpike$NAME,log="y",cex.axis=0.7)

Other plot types

If you want to make a histogram, hist will probably work.

hist(d$TP)

Other plot types

These and many other functions exist, and they're not too hard to find. Just google them (e.g., "R histogram"). Feel free to try to find other plot types that you can make in R on your own.

Customizing plots

For now though, let's go back to our basic scatterplot and learn how to customize it (aka, add complexity and make it pretty).

plot(d$TP,d$CHL)

Customizing plots

For simplicity, let's limit it to one lake:

kentuck = d[d$NAME=="Kentuck Lake - Site 2-East End-Deep Hole",]
plot(kentuck$TP,kentuck$CHL)

Customizing plots

First, let's say we want to make a scatterplot with an overlayed line that compares our points to an existing model. The general approach in R is to first create your simple plot, and then add features to it. You can add features with a number of functions, including lines, points, polygon, and more. These don't create plots on their own - they add lines, points, or a polygon to a plot that has already been made and is currently active.

For our example, we'll use the 2nd data.frame from our project folder, which already has modeled chlorophyll as a function of TP. The units are log-transformed though, so we'll untransform using exp.

plot(kentuck$TP,kentuck$CHL)
lines(exp(model$logTP),exp(model$fit))

Customizing plots

plot(kentuck$TP, kentuck$CHL)
lines(exp(model$logTP), exp(model$fit))

Great, now you have 2 layers! 'Tis a shame that it's pretty ugly! Let's spruce it up!

Customizing plots

You may have noticed that in the plot help file, there are many arguments, including xlab and ylab to name your axes and main for the plot title. These arguments require text strings:

plot(kentuck$TP,kentuck$CHL,
     xlab="Total Phosphorus",
     ylab="Chlorophyll",
     main="") #this makes sure that the title is left blank

Customizing plots

Then, in the help files for plot, lines, etc., there is something called "Further graphical parameters (see par)…". par is essentially a set of default parameters. Use ?par to see the numerous options. We won't walk through them all now, but they are worth exploring. Many of them can be changed within the plot command. Let's take a look at some common ones

Customizing plots

argument description example
log log-transform axes? log="x"
col symbol color col="blue"
bg background color of a symbol bg="skyblue"
pch dot type pch=21
cex text and symbol size (relative to 1) cex=1.5
lty line type lty=2
lwd line width lwd=3
las axis label direction las=1

Customizing plots

Let's first use the log argument to log both axes.

plot(kentuck$TP,kentuck$CHL,
     log="xy", #transforms both axes into log-scale
     xlab="Total Phosphorus",ylab="Chlorophyll",main="") 
lines(exp(model$logTP),exp(model$fit))

Customizing plots

Now, let's change the point and line types. A simple way to find what types are available is to google "r pch" or "r lty".

plot(kentuck$TP,kentuck$CHL,log="xy",
     pch=21,
     xlab="Total Phosphorus",ylab="Chlorophyll",main="") 
lines(exp(model$logTP),exp(model$fit),
      lty=2)

Customizing plots

Now, add some color. Colors can be pretty intuitive ("black","red", etc.). You can also google image "r colors" to see pre-named colors, or you can provide RGB codes in the form "#RRGGBB", or use existing color palettes and functions (e.g. (rainbow).

plot(kentuck$TP,kentuck$CHL,log="xy",pch=21,
     col="seagreen",bg="seagreen1",
     xlab="Total Phosphorus",ylab="Chlorophyll",main="") 
lines(exp(model$logTP),exp(model$fit),lty=2,
      col="seagreen4")

Customizing plots

plot(kentuck$TP,kentuck$CHL,log="xy",pch=21,
     col="seagreen",bg="seagreen1",
     xlab="Total Phosphorus",ylab="Chlorophyll",main="") 
lines(exp(model$logTP),exp(model$fit),lty=2,
      col="seagreen4")

Customizing plots

Now, let's increase the dot size and line thickness

plot(kentuck$TP,kentuck$CHL,pch=21,col="seagreen",bg="seagreen1",
     cex=1.2,
     xlab="Total Phosphorus",ylab="Chlorophyll",main="",log="xy") 
lines(exp(model$logTP),exp(model$fit),lty=2,col="seagreen4",
      lwd=2)

Customizing plots

Change the orientation of the axis-tick labels (so they all read left-to-right)

plot(kentuck$TP,kentuck$CHL,pch=21,col="seagreen",bg="seagreen1",cex=1.2,
     las=1,
     xlab="Total Phosphorus",ylab="Chlorophyll",main="",log="xy")
lines(exp(model$logTP),exp(model$fit),lty=2,col="seagreen4",lwd=2)

Customizing plots

Now, let's finally try to get rid of that useless white space at the top of our plot. To do that, we'll introduce a new way to control par settings.

There are some arguments that can only be set in a specific call to the par function, instead of within plot. mar is an argument thats takes a vector of 4 values, where each is the number of lines of space provided on each side of the plot in the form c(bottom, left, top, right). The default is c(5.1,4.1,4.1,2). So, R is providing 4.1 lines of space above the plot (the 3rd value in that vector). To reduce that to something small, we just reset its value in par: par(mar=c(5.1,4.1,0.5,2)).

Customizing plots

par(mar=c(4,4,0.25,0.25))
plot(kentuck$TP,kentuck$CHL,pch=21,col="seagreen",bg="seagreen1",
     cex=1.2,las=1,xlab="Total Phosphorus",
     ylab="Chlorophyll",main="",log="xy") 
lines(exp(model$logTP),exp(model$fit),lty=2,col="seagreen4",lwd=2)

Customizing plots

One of the things that par allows us to do is multi-panel plotting. Perhaps you noticed that each time you ran the plot function, the previous plot was overwritten. What if you wanted two plots on the same figure, next to each other? Before creating the first plot, we can use par to tell R that we're going to create 2 plots in the figure. There are two par arguments that control this: mfrow and mfcol. I think of the "mf" as "multiple figures" and "col" or "row" to indicate the number of columns or rows, respectively, and how many items in each one. Thus, par(mfrow=c(3,2)) creates a 6-panel plot with 3 rows of 2 items (columns) each. To make two plots side-by-side, we can use par(mfrow=c(1,2)).

Customizing plots

#first make a data.frame for a different lake to plot in the 2nd panel
sTwin = d[d$NAME=="South Twin Lake - Deep Hole",]

#set up our plot

par(mar=c(4,4,.3,.3),
  mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(kentuck$TP,kentuck$CHL,pch=21,col="seagreen",bg="seagreen1",
     cex=1.2,las=1,xlab="Total Phosphorus",
     ylab="Chlorophyll",main="",log="xy") 
lines(exp(model$logTP),exp(model$fit),lty=2,col="seagreen4",lwd=2)

plot(sTwin$TP,sTwin$CHL,pch=21,col="seagreen",bg="seagreen1",
     cex=1.2,las=1,xlab="Total Phosphorus",
     ylab="Chlorophyll",main="",log="xy") 
lines(exp(model$logTP),exp(model$fit),lty=2,col="seagreen4",lwd=2)

Customizing plots

Customizing plots

Let's improve this plot by doing 2 things to make it easier to compare between lakes

  1. Set the axis limits so that they are equal between the two plots
  2. Add a label identifying each lake

Customizing plots

To set the axis limits, we can use the arguments xlim and ylim in conjunction with the range function to find the min and max.

xlimits = range(c(kentuck$TP,sTwin$TP))
ylimits = range(c(kentuck$CHL,sTwin$CHL))

Customizing plots

par(mfrow=c(1,2),mar=c(4,4,.3,.3))  
plot(kentuck$TP,kentuck$CHL,pch=21,col="seagreen",bg="seagreen1",cex=1.2,
     xlim=xlimits,ylim=ylimits,
     las=1,xlab="Total Phosphorus",ylab="Chlorophyll",main="",log="xy") 
lines(exp(model$logTP),exp(model$fit),lty=2,col="seagreen4",lwd=2)

plot(sTwin$TP,sTwin$CHL,pch=21,col="seagreen",bg="seagreen1",cex=1.2,
     xlim=xlimits,ylim=ylimits,
     las=1,xlab="Total Phosphorus",ylab="Chlorophyll",main="",log="xy") 
lines(exp(model$logTP),exp(model$fit),lty=2,col="seagreen4",lwd=2)

Customizing plots

Customizing plots

We could easily add Lake Name labels with the main argument in plot. However, in this case we'd prefer to have the lake names in the upper left space within the plots.

To do this, we can use the text or legend function. These work like lines in that they plot onto an active graphic. For text, you supply the x & y coordinates where the text should go, and the text itself. In this case, we'll use legend to take advantage of its use of location keywords (e.g., "topleft").

legend("topleft", #give the location by keyword
       "Kentuck Lake", #the contents of the legend
       bty="n") #bty means box type around legend, "n" means none

Customizing plots

par(mfrow=c(1,2),mar=c(4,4,.3,.3)) 
plot(kentuck$TP,kentuck$CHL,pch=21,col="seagreen",bg="seagreen1",
     cex=1.2,las=1,xlim=xlimits,ylim=ylimits,
     xlab="Total Phosphorus",ylab="Chlorophyll",main="",log="xy",) 
lines(exp(model$logTP),exp(model$fit),lty=2,col="seagreen4",lwd=2)
legend("topleft","Kentuck Lake",bty="n")

plot(sTwin$TP,sTwin$CHL,pch=21,col="seagreen",bg="seagreen1",
     cex=1.2,las=1,xlim=xlimits,ylim=ylimits,
     xlab="Total Phosphorus",ylab="Chlorophyll",main="",log="xy") 
lines(exp(model$logTP),exp(model$fit),lty=2,col="seagreen4",lwd=2)
legend("topleft","South Twin Lake",bty="n")

Customizing plots

Saving plots

Finally, what if we want to save our plot outside of R? The recommended strategy is to use a graphic devices function, which give you full control over dimensions, resolution, background color, etc. The functions are named pretty intuitively: pdf, png, jpeg, tiff, etc.

Key arguments: filename, width, height, units, and res

  • units can be "px" (default), "in", "cm", or "mm". I generally use "in", as these are typically easy to fit onto a slide or a page. Then, you can set width and height to desired dimensions (width=6, height=4).
  • res defines the dots/pixels per inch for bitmap type images. Generally, 150 is sufficient for presentations, 300 is good for print, but some publications require higher.
  • filename is your desired file name and extension

Saving plots

Example:

png("MyNewFigure.png",
    units="in",
    width=6.5, #sized for paper width between margins
    height=3.5,
    res=300)

Saving plots

So how do you get that function to work with your plotting code?

When you run png, nothing seems to happen in RStudio. However, behind the scenes, R opens a new graphical device, onto which all the subsequent lines of code will be run and plotted. At the end of those lines of code, we need to tell R to stop the plotting and save the .png file. We can do this by telling R to shut off the graphical device. We do that by running dev.off. Let's see how all this comes together to create and save a figure…

Saving plots

png("MyNewFigure.png",units="in",width=6.5,height=3.5,res=300)
par(mfrow=c(1,2),mar=c(4,4,.3,.3)) 
plot(kentuck$TP,kentuck$CHL,pch=21,col="seagreen",bg="seagreen1",
     cex=1.2,las=1,xlim=xlimits,ylim=ylimits,
     xlab="Total Phosphorus",ylab="Chlorophyll",main="",log="xy",) 
lines(exp(model$logTP),exp(model$fit),lty=2,col="seagreen4",lwd=2)
legend("topleft","Kentuck Lake",bty="n")

plot(sTwin$TP,sTwin$CHL,pch=21,col="seagreen",bg="seagreen1",
     cex=1.2,las=1,xlim=xlimits,ylim=ylimits,
     xlab="Total Phosphorus",ylab="Chlorophyll",main="",log="xy") 
lines(exp(model$logTP),exp(model$fit),lty=2,col="seagreen4",lwd=2)
legend("topleft","South Twin Lake",bty="n")
dev.off()

Saving plots

You should now be able to find your saved figure in the project folder. Open it to see what it looks like. Note that the sizing of items may not match the way RStudio showed it to you.

5-MINUTE BREAK

Data analysis with R

So far, we've presented the basics of using R, and gone into some depth in exploring plots, which are a natural early step in data analysis. R is also a powerful statistical platform. Base R includes most basic statistical functions. There are also R packages for pretty much any statistical method you have heard of, from mixed effects models, to classification and regression trees, to ordination, to artificial neural networks, and many more…

In this workshop, we will demonstrate the use of a few common statistical methods, including setting up the data frame, writing the model formula, and working with the results. This is not a statistics course, so we won't cover the appropriate uses of these methods.

Data format

Most statistical functions require that your data be formatted as a data frame with variable names as column names. Let's use the kentuck data frame for the example.

str(kentuck)
## 'data.frame':    102 obs. of  5 variables:
##  $ ID  : int  643451 643451 643451 643451 643451 643451 643451 643451 643451 643451 ...
##  $ NAME: Factor w/ 200 levels "Afterglow Lake - Deep Hole",..: 81 81 81 81 81 81 81 81 81 81 ...
##  $ DATE: Date, format: "1999-07-19" "2000-09-25" ...
##  $ CHL : num  11 9 1.47 13.6 7.02 5.08 7.13 15.7 16.1 8.08 ...
##  $ TP  : num  37 26 17 23 24 16 27 38 29 27 ...

Regression

lm() (linear model) is the basic regression function. The required arguments are formula and data.

In lm(), the model formula specifies the response and predictor variable(s), any interactions among predictors, and may include variable transformations.

For example,

model1 = lm(log(CHL)~log(TP),kentuck)

will fit a regression between log(TP) and log(CHL) for Kentuck Lake and assign the resulting model object to the variable model1.

Regression

model object

You can print a summary of the model results with

summary(model1)

t-test

t.test performs one and two sample unpaired or two sample paired t-tests. The only required arguments are the vector(s) of data.

Example: There appears to be an abrupt increase in chlorophyll in Kentuck Lake around 2011. We can use t.test to test whether the mean chlorophyll before 2011 is signficantly different from the mean chlorophyll after 2010.

t-test

early = kentuck$CHL[kentuck$DATE<as.Date("2011-01-01")]
late = kentuck$CHL[kentuck$DATE>=as.Date("2011-01-01")]
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
hist(early)
hist(late)

t-test

t.test(log(early),log(late))
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  log(early) and log(late)
## t = -6.1524, df = 99.992, p-value = 1.586e-08
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -1.2654171 -0.6482979
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  2.139396  3.096254

Data management

Philosophies/Rules

Say you have a task where you need to retrieve a dataset, manipulate the data in a multi-step process, analyze the manipulated data, and return a result. One way to accomplish this task would be to use Excel. If you choose to use Excel, and most of your colleagues use Excel as well, your workflow may look something like…

Data management

Philosophies/Rules

  1. Open a second-hand .xlsx file, try to understand what the names of the worksheets mean, and hope you select the correct data given that there are bits of fragmented tables on each worksheet.
  2. Create a new .xlsx file, copy and paste your data into it, and save.
  3. Create several new worksheets in your .xlsx file, each associated with an intermediate calculation.
  4. Send your third-hand .xlsx file to your client/colleague, and they will repeat the above process for their task.

Data management

Philosophies/Rules

With your new R skills (and working with your colleagues with new R skills), you will be able to improve your workflow to look something like this:

  1. Retrieve your data from the original source.
  2. Write a script that contains all intermediate processing steps without needing to save any intermediate data.
  3. Send your results to your client in a simple, text-based file format such as tab-delimited.

Data management

Philosophies/Rules

The benefits of the R-driven process is this:

  1. Each step in your retrieval, manipultation, analysis, and delivery process is well-documented and repeatable.
  2. You are confident you are using the correct data, you have not altered the original data in the process, and you have not created any uneccessary clutter on your hard-drive with intermediate data files.
  3. Your data result will be readable 20-30 years from now even though Excel has been deprecated.

Data management

Philosophies/Rules

To distill the above process, here are a few general guidelines:

  1. Refer to the original dataset without altering it
  2. Create as few intermediate datasets as possible
  3. Save your product in a simple, timeless data format

There are, of course, exceptions to the above rules, but these 3 will serve you well for most tasks.

Data management

Files

With respect to data management, there are two sets of functions that will serve you well. The first is the file.* family of functions:

file.create("new_file.txt")
file.remove("old_file.txt")
file.rename("new_file.txt", "new_file2.txt")
file.copy("new_file.txt", "new_file2.txt")

Data management

Files

The second set is the write.* family of functions:

# Write a vector of data
write(x, file="new_file.txt")
# Write character lines
writeLines(x, "new_file.txt")
# Write a text-based delimited data table
write.table(x, "new_file.txt")
write.csv(x, "new_file.txt")

Notice that the above files have no file path…

Data management

Files

If a file path is not explicitly defined, R will write to your working directory. You can view the working directory using the getwd function:

getwd()
## [1] "E:/Working documents/Users/latzka/Documents/Latzka work docs/r_workshop"

Data management

Files

If you want to change the working directory, use the setwd function:

setwd("C:/Users")

Data management

Files

A helpful shortcut is to use the tilde character (~) in place of your home directory:

setwd("~")
getwd()
## [1] "C:/Users/latzka/Documents"

Data management

Files

Another helpful shortcut is using two dots (..) to represent one folder up:

setwd("~/..")
getwd()
## [1] "C:/Users/latzka"

Data management

Files

Working with lots of files:

dir.create("temp")
phrase = "All work and no play makes Jack a dull boy"
for (i in 1:500) {
  newfile = paste("temp/file", i, ".txt", sep="")
  writeLines(rep(phrase, 100), newfile)
}
setwd("temp")
newfiles = list.files()
file.remove(newfiles)

Data management

Databases

If we're going to take our data management philosophies to heart, we will need to learn how to use our databases. WDNR uses Oracle databases, and therefore we will need a special package to help us read data using R.

Tangent

Packages

Packages in R are like "plug-ins" to the basic language that extend its functionality, and they are what make R special.

Packages are community driven, and the community includes very talented individuals all the way up to giant corporations such as Oracle.

There is an R package for just about anything you can think of. All official R packages are stored in the Comprehensive R Archive Network, or CRAN.

Spatial Analysis

A complete GIS is available to you for free!:

  • Vector (rgeos package) and raster (raster package) processing/analysis
  • Robust library of coordinate systems, projections, and file type support using rgdal package
  • Static cartography with extremely flexible base plot function and ggplot2 and ggmap packages, and web cartography through leaflet including linkage with Shiny!
  • Spatial statistics: kriging and model-fitting (gstat and SSN), point-pattern analysis (spatstat)

For more information, see:

http://asruesch.github.io/GeRgraphyPresentation/

Awesome Data Visualization!

Even the pros use it!
